# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: saml-federation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:saml-federation/federated-identity] A **federated identity** in information technology is the means of linking a person's electronic identity and attributes, stored across multiple distinct identity management systems.
[src:saml-federation/federated-identity] Federated identity is related to single sign-on (SSO), in which a user's single authentication ticket, or token, is trusted across multiple IT systems or even organizations.
[src:saml-federation/federated-identity] SSO is a subset of federated identity management, as it relates only to authentication and is understood on the level of technical interoperability, and it would not be possible without some sort of federation.
[src:saml-federation/federated-identity] In information technology (IT), federated identity management (FIdM) amounts to having a common set of policies, practices and protocols in place to manage the identity and trust into IT users and devices across organizations.
[src:saml-federation/federated-identity] Single sign-on (SSO) systems allow a single user authentication process across multiple IT systems or even organizations.
[src:saml-federation/federated-identity] SSO is a subset of federated identity management, as it relates only to authentication and technical interoperability.
[src:saml-federation/federated-identity] Centralized identity management solutions were created to help deal with user and data security where the user and the systems they accessed were within the same network – or at least the same "domain of control".
[src:saml-federation/federated-identity] Increasingly, however, users are accessing external systems which are fundamentally outside their domain of control, and external users are accessing internal systems.
[src:saml-federation/federated-identity] The increasingly common separation of the user from the systems requiring access is an inevitable by-product of the decentralization brought about by the integration of the Internet into every aspect of both personal and business life.
[src:saml-federation/federated-identity] Evolving identity management challenges, and especially the challenges associated with cross-company, cross-domain access, have given rise to a new approach to identity management, known now as "federated identity management".
[src:saml-federation/federated-identity] FIdM, or the "federation" of identity, describes the technologies, standards and use-cases which serve to enable the portability of identity information across otherwise autonomous security domains.
[src:saml-federation/federated-identity] The ultimate goal of identity federation is to enable users of one domain to securely access data or systems of another domain seamlessly, and without the need for completely redundant user administration.
[src:saml-federation/federated-identity] Identity federation comes in many flavors, including "user-controlled" or "user-centric" scenarios, as well as enterprise-controlled or business-to-business scenarios.
[src:saml-federation/federated-identity] Federation is enabled through the use of open industry standards and/or openly published specifications, such that multiple parties can achieve interoperability for common use-cases.
[src:saml-federation/federated-identity] Typical use-cases involve things such as cross-domain, web-based single sign-on, cross-domain user account provisioning, cross-domain entitlement management and cross-domain user attribute exchange.
[src:saml-federation/federated-identity] Use of identity federation standards can reduce cost by eliminating the need to scale one-off or proprietary solutions.
[src:saml-federation/federated-identity] It can increase security and lower risk by enabling an organization to identify and authenticate a user once, and then use that identity information across multiple systems, including external partner websites.
[src:saml-federation/federated-identity] It can improve privacy compliance by allowing the user to control what information is shared, or by limiting the amount of information shared.
[src:saml-federation/federated-identity] And lastly, it can drastically improve the end-user experience by eliminating the need for new account registration through automatic "federated provisioning" or the need to redundantly login through cross-domain single sign-on.
[src:saml-federation/federated-identity] The notion of identity federation is extremely broad, and also evolving.
[src:saml-federation/federated-identity] It could involve user-to-user and user-to-application as well as application-to-application use-case scenarios at both the browser tier and the web services or service-oriented architecture (SOA) tier.
[src:saml-federation/federated-identity] It can involve high-trust, high-security scenarios as well as low-trust, low-security scenarios.
[src:saml-federation/federated-identity] The levels of identity assurance that may be required for a given scenario are also being standardized through a common and open Identity Assurance Framework.
[src:saml-federation/federated-identity] It can involve user-centric use-cases, as well as enterprise-centric use-cases.
[src:saml-federation/federated-identity] The term "identity federation" is by design a generic term, and is not bound to any one specific protocol, technology, implementation or company.
[src:saml-federation/federated-identity] Identity federations may be bi-lateral relationships or multilateral relationships.
[src:saml-federation/federated-identity] In the latter case, the multilateral federation frequently occurs in a vertical market, such as in law enforcement (such as the National Identity Exchange Federation - NIEF), and research and education (such as InCommon).
[src:saml-federation/federated-identity] If the identity federation is bilateral, the two parties can exchange the necessary metadata (assertion signing keys, etc.) to implement the relationship.
[src:saml-federation/federated-identity] In a multilateral federation, the metadata exchange among participants is a more complex issue.
[src:saml-federation/federated-identity] It can be handled in a hub-and-spoke exchange or by the distribution of a metadata aggregate by a federated operator.
[src:saml-federation/federated-identity] One thing that is consistent, however, is the fact that "federation" describes methods of identity portability which are achieved in an open, often standards-based manner – meaning anyone adhering to the open specification or standard can achieve the full spectrum of use-cases and interoperability.
[src:saml-federation/federated-identity] Identity federation can be accomplished any number of ways, some of which involve the use of formal Internet standards, such as the OASIS Security Assertion Markup Language (SAML) specification, and some of which may involve open-source technologies and/or other openly published specifications (e.g.
[src:saml-federation/federated-identity] Information Cards, OpenID, the Higgins trust framework or Novell's Bandit project).
[src:saml-federation/federated-identity] Technologies used for federated identity include SAML (Security Assertion Markup Language), OAuth, OpenID, Security Tokens (Simple Web Tokens, JSON Web Tokens, and SAML assertions), Web Service Specifications, and Windows Identity Foundation.
[src:saml-federation/federated-identity] The Federal Risk and Authorization Management Program (FedRAMP) is a government-wide program that provides a standardized approach to security assessment, authorization, and continuous monitoring for cloud products and services.
[src:saml-federation/federated-identity] The FedRAMP program supports the transition of federal agencies from legacy IT infrastructure to cloud-based computing environments.
[src:saml-federation/federated-identity] Here is a list of services that provide social login features which they encourage other websites to use.
[src:saml-federation/federated-identity] Related are federated identity login providers.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] The terms "identity management" (IdM) and "identity and access management" are used interchangeably in the area of identity access management.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] Identity-management systems, products, applications and platforms manage identifying and ancillary data about entities that include individuals, computer-related hardware, and software applications.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] IdM covers issues such as how users gain an identity, the roles, and sometimes the permissions that identity grants, the protection of that identity, and the technologies supporting that protection (e.g., network protocols, digital certificates, passwords, etc.).
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] Identity management (IdM) is the task of controlling information about users on computers.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] Such information includes information that authenticates the identity of a user, and information that describes data and actions they are authorized to access and/or perform.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] It also includes the management of descriptive information about the user and how and by whom that information can be accessed and modified.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] In addition to users, managed entities typically include hardware and network resources and even applications.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] The diagram below shows the relationship between the configuration and operation phases of IAM, as well as the distinction between identity management and access management.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] Access control is the enforcement of access rights defined as part of access authorization.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] Digital identity is an entity's online presence, encompassing personal identifying information (PII) and ancillary information.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] See OECD and NIST guidelines on protecting PII.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] It can be interpreted as the codification of identity names and attributes of a physical instance in a way that facilitates processing.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] A general model of identity can be constructed from a small set of axioms, for example that all identities in a given namespace are unique, or that such identities bear a specific relationship to corresponding entities in the real world.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] Such an axiomatic model expresses "pure identity" in the sense that the model is not constrained by a specific application context.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] In general, an entity (real or virtual) can have multiple identities and each identity can encompass multiple attributes, some of which are unique within a given name space.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] The diagram below illustrates the conceptual relationship between identities and entities, as well as between identities and their attributes.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] In most theoretical and all practical models of digital identity, a given identity object consists of a finite set of properties (attribute values).
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] These properties record information about the object, either for purposes external to the model or to operate the model, for example in classification and retrieval.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] A "pure identity" model is strictly not concerned with the external semantics of these properties.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] The most common departure from "pure identity" in practice occurs with properties intended to assure some aspect of identity, for example a digital signature or software token which the model may use internally to verify some aspect of the identity in satisfaction of an external purpose.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] To the extent that the model expresses such semantics internally, it is not a pure model.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] Contrast this situation with properties that might be externally used for purposes of information security such as managing access or entitlement, but which are simply stored, maintained and retrieved, without special treatment by the model.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] The absence of external semantics within the model qualifies it as a "pure identity" model.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] Identity management can thus be defined as a set of operations on a given identity model, or more generally, as a set of capabilities with reference to it.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] In practice, identity management often expands to express how model content is to be provisioned and reconciled among multiple identity models.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] The process of reconciling accounts may also be referred to as de-provisioning.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] User access enables users to assume a specific digital identity across applications, which enables access controls to be assigned and evaluated against this identity.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] The use of a single identity for a given user across multiple systems eases tasks for administrators and users.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] It simplifies access monitoring and verification, and allows the organizations to minimize excessive privileges granted to one user.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] Ensuring user access security is crucial in this process, as it involves protecting the integrity and confidentiality of user credentials and preventing unauthorized access.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] Implementing robust authentication mechanisms, such as multi-factor authentication (MFA), regular security audits, and strict access controls, helps safeguard user identities and sensitive data.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] User access can be tracked from initiation to termination of user access.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] When organizations deploy an identity management process or system, their motivation is normally not primarily to manage a set of identities, but rather to grant appropriate access rights to those entities via their identities.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] In other words, access management is normally the motivation for identity management and the two sets of processes are consequently closely related.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] Organizations continue to add services for both internal users and by customers.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] Many such services require identity management to properly provide these services.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] Increasingly, identity management has been partitioned from application functions so that a single identity can serve many or even all of an organization's activities.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] For internal use identity management is evolving to control access to all digital assets, including devices, network equipment, servers, portals, content, applications and/or products.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] Services often require access to extensive information about a user, including address books, preferences, entitlements and contact information.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] Since much of this information is subject to privacy and/or confidentiality requirements, controlling access to it is vital.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] Identity federation comprises one or more systems that share user access and allow users to log in based on authenticating against one of the systems participating in the federation.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] This trust between several systems is often known as a "circle of trust".
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] In this setup, one system acts as the identity provider (IdP) and other systems act as service providers (SPs).
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] When a user needs to access some service controlled by SP, they first authenticate against the IdP.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] Upon successful authentication, the IdP sends a secure "assertion" to the SP.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] "SAML assertions, specified using a markup language intended for describing security assertions, can be used by a verifier to make a statement to a relying party about the identity of a claimant.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] In addition to creation, deletion, modification of user identity data either assisted or self-service, identity management controls ancillary entity data for use by applications, such as contact information or location.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] Putting personal information onto computer networks necessarily raises privacy concerns.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] Absent proper protections, the data may be used to implement a surveillance society.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] Social web and online social networking services make heavy use of identity management.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] Helping users decide how to manage access to their personal information has become an issue of broad concern.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] Research related to the management of identity covers disciplines such as technology, social sciences, humanities and the law.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] Decentralized identity management is identity management based on decentralized identifiers (DIDs).
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] Within the Seventh Research Framework Programme of the European Union from 2007 to 2013, several new projects related to Identity Management started.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] The PICOS Project investigates and develops a state-of-the-art platform for providing trust, privacy and identity management in mobile communities.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] SWIFT focuses on extending identity functions and federation to the network while addressing usability and privacy concerns and leverages identity technology as a key to integrate service and transport infrastructures for the benefit of users and the providers.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] Ongoing projects include Future of Identity in the Information Society (FIDIS), GUIDE, and PRIME.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] In each organization there is normally a role or department that is responsible for managing the schema of digital identities of their staff and their own objects, which are represented by object identities or object identifiers (OID).
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] The organizational policies and processes and procedures related to the oversight of identity management are sometimes referred to as *Identity Governance and Administration* (IGA).
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] How effectively and appropriately such tools are used falls within scope of broader governance, risk management, and compliance regimes.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] An **identity-management system** refers to an information system, or to a set of technologies that can be used for enterprise or cross-network identity management.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] Identity and access management systems are central to meeting regulatory requirements across multiple sectors that mandate controls over who can access sensitive information.
[src:saml-federation/identity-management] NIST Special Publication 800-53 includes comprehensive identity and access management controls in the AC (Access Control) and IA (Identification and Authentication) control families, providing the reference framework for federal agency IAM implementations.
[src:saml-federation/identity-provider] An **identity provider** (abbreviated **IdP**, **IDP**, or **idp**) is a system entity that creates, maintains, and manages identity information for principals and also provides authentication services to relying applications within a federation or distributed network.
[src:saml-federation/identity-provider] Identity providers offer user authentication as a service.
[src:saml-federation/identity-provider] Relying party applications, such as web applications, outsource the user authentication step to a trusted identity provider.
[src:saml-federation/identity-provider] Such a relying party application is said to be *federated*, that is, it consumes federated identity.
[src:saml-federation/identity-provider] An identity provider is “a trusted provider that lets you use single sign-on (SSO) to access other websites.” SSO enhances usability by reducing password fatigue.
[src:saml-federation/identity-provider] It also provides better security by decreasing the potential attack surface.
[src:saml-federation/identity-provider] Identity providers can facilitate connections between cloud computing resources and users, thus decreasing the need for users to re-authenticate when using mobile and roaming applications.
[src:saml-federation/identity-provider] OpenID Connect (OIDC) is an identity layer on top of OAuth.
[src:saml-federation/identity-provider] In the domain model associated with OIDC, an identity provider is a special type of OAuth 2.0 authorization server.
[src:saml-federation/identity-provider] Specifically, a system entity called an OpenID Provider issues JSON-formatted identity tokens to OIDC relying parties via a RESTful HTTP API.
[src:saml-federation/identity-provider] The Security Assertion Markup Language (SAML) is a set of profiles for exchanging authentication and authorization data across security domains.
[src:saml-federation/identity-provider] In the SAML domain model, an identity provider is a special type of authentication authority.
[src:saml-federation/identity-provider] Specifically, a SAML identity provider is a system entity that issues authentication assertions in conjunction with an SSO profile of SAML.
[src:saml-federation/identity-provider] A relying party that consumes these authentication assertions is called a SAML service provider.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] An important use case that SAML addresses is web-browser single sign-on (SSO).
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Single sign-on is relatively easy to accomplish within a security domain (using cookies, for example) but extending SSO across security domains is more difficult and resulted in the proliferation of non-interoperable proprietary technologies.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] The SAML Web Browser SSO profile was specified and standardized to promote interoperability.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] In practice, SAML SSO is most commonly used for authentication into cloud-based business software.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] The SAML specification defines three roles: the principal (typically a human user), the identity provider (IdP) and the service provider (SP).
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] In the primary use case addressed by SAML, the principal requests a service from the service provider.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] The service provider requests and obtains an authentication assertion from the identity provider.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] On the basis of this assertion, the service provider can make an access control decision, that is, it can decide whether to perform the service for the connected principal.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] At the heart of the SAML assertion is a subject (a principal within the context of a particular security domain) about which something is being asserted.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] The subject is usually (but not necessarily) a human.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] As in the SAML 2.0 Technical Overview, the terms subject and principal are used interchangeably.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Before delivering the subject-based assertion from Identity Provider to the Service Provider, the Identity Provider may request some information from the principal (such as a user name and password) in order to authenticate the principal.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML specifies the content of the assertion that is passed from the Identity Provider to the Service Provider.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] In SAML, one Identity Provider may provide SAML assertions to many Service Providers.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Similarly, one Service Provider (SP) may rely on and trust assertions from many independent Identity Providers (IdP).
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML does not specify the method of authentication at the identity provider.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] The IdP may use a username and password, or some other form of authentication, including multi-factor authentication or Kerberos tickets.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] A directory service such as RADIUS or LDAP that allows users to log in with a user name and password is a typical source of authentication tokens at an identity provider.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] The popular Internet social networking services also provide identity services that in theory could be used to support SAML exchanges.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Building on these initial contributions, in November 2002 OASIS announced the Security Assertion Markup Language (SAML) 1.0 specification as an OASIS Standard.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Meanwhile, the Liberty Alliance, a large consortium of companies, non-profit and government organizations, proposed an extension to the SAML standard called the Liberty Identity Federation Framework (ID-FF).
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Like its SAML predecessor, Liberty ID-FF proposed a standardized, cross-domain, web-based, single sign-on framework.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] In addition, Liberty described a *circle of trust* where each participating domain is trusted to accurately document the processes used to identify a user, the type of authentication system used, and any policies associated with the resulting authentication credentials.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Other members of the circle of trust could then examine these policies to determine whether to trust such information.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] While Liberty was developing ID-FF, the SSTC began work on a minor upgrade to the SAML standard.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] The resulting SAML 1.1 specification was ratified by the SSTC in September 2003.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Then, in November of that same year, Liberty contributed ID-FF 1.2 to OASIS, thereby sowing the seeds for the next major version of SAML.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] In March 2005, SAML 2.0 was announced as an OASIS Standard.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML 2.0 represents the convergence of Liberty ID-FF and proprietary extensions contributed by the Shibboleth project, as well as early versions of SAML itself.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Most SAML implementations support v2.0 while many still support v1.1 for backward compatibility.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] By January 2008, deployments of SAML 2.0 became common in government, higher education, and commercial enterprises worldwide.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML has undergone one minor and one major revision since 1.0.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Versions 1.0 and 1.1 of SAML are similar even though small differences exist., however, the differences between SAML 2.0 and SAML 1.1 are substantial.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Although the two standards address the same use case, SAML 2.0 is incompatible with its predecessor.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Although ID-FF 1.2 was contributed to OASIS as the basis of SAML 2.0, there are some important differences between SAML 2.0 and ID-FF 1.2.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] In particular, the two specifications, despite their common roots, are incompatible.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML defines XML-based assertions and protocols, bindings, and profiles.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] The term *SAML Core* refers to the general syntax and semantics of SAML assertions as well as the protocol used to request and transmit those assertions from one system entity to another.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] *SAML protocol* refers to **what** is transmitted, not **how** (the latter is determined by the choice of binding).
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] So SAML Core defines "bare" SAML assertions along with SAML request and response elements.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] A *SAML binding* determines how SAML requests and responses map onto standard messaging or communications protocols.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] An important (synchronous) binding is the SAML SOAP binding.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] A *SAML profile* is a concrete manifestation of a defined use case using a particular combination of assertions, protocols and bindings.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML assertions are usually transferred from identity providers to service providers.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Assertions contain *statements* that service providers use to make access-control decisions.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] An *attribute statement* asserts that a principal is associated with certain attributes.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] An *attribute* is simply a name–value pair.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Relying parties use attributes to make access-control decisions.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] An *authorization decision statement* asserts that a principal is permitted to perform action *A* on resource *R* given evidence *E*.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] The expressiveness of authorization decision statements in SAML is intentionally limited.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] More-advanced use cases are encouraged to use XACML instead.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] A SAML *protocol* describes how certain SAML elements (including assertions) are packaged within SAML request and response elements, and gives the processing rules that SAML entities must follow when producing or consuming these elements.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] For the most part, a SAML protocol is a simple request-response protocol.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] The most important type of SAML protocol request is called a *query*.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] A service provider makes a query directly to an identity provider over a secure back channel.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Thus query messages are typically bound to SOAP.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] The result of an attribute query is a SAML response containing an assertion, which itself contains an attribute statement.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] See the SAML 2.0 topic for an example of attribute query/response.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Beyond queries, SAML 1.1 specifies no other protocols.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML 2.0 expands the notion of *protocol* considerably.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Most of these protocols are new in SAML 2.0.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] A SAML *binding* is a mapping of a SAML protocol message onto standard messaging formats and/or communications protocols.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] For example, the SAML SOAP binding specifies how a SAML message is encapsulated in a SOAP envelope, which itself is bound to an HTTP message.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML 1.1 specifies just one binding, the SAML SOAP Binding.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] In addition to SOAP, implicit in SAML 1.1 Web Browser SSO are the precursors of the HTTP POST Binding, the HTTP Redirect Binding, and the HTTP Artifact Binding.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] These are not defined explicitly, however, and are only used in conjunction with SAML 1.1 Web Browser SSO.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] The notion of binding is not fully developed until SAML 2.0.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML 2.0 completely separates the binding concept from the underlying profile.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] A SAML *profile* describes in detail how SAML assertions, protocols, and bindings combine to support a defined use case.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] The most important SAML profile is the Web Browser SSO Profile.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML 1.1 specifies two forms of Web Browser SSO, the Browser/Artifact Profile and the Browser/POST Profile.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] The latter passes assertions *by value* whereas Browser/Artifact passes assertions *by reference*.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] As a consequence, Browser/Artifact requires a back-channel SAML exchange over SOAP.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] In SAML 1.1, all flows begin with a request at the identity provider for simplicity.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Proprietary extensions to the basic IdP-initiated flow have been proposed (by Shibboleth, for example).
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] The Web Browser SSO Profile was completely refactored for SAML 2.0.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Conceptually, SAML 1.1 Browser/Artifact and Browser/POST are special cases of SAML 2.0 Web Browser SSO.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] The latter is considerably more flexible than its SAML 1.1 counterpart due to the new "plug-and-play" binding design of SAML 2.0.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Unlike previous versions, SAML 2.0 browser flows begin with a request at the service provider.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] This provides greater flexibility, but SP-initiated flows naturally give rise to the so-called *Identity Provider Discovery* problem, the focus of much research today.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Requirements are often phrased in terms of (mutual) authentication, integrity, and confidentiality, leaving the choice of security mechanism to implementers and deployers.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] The primary SAML use case is called *Web Browser Single Sign-On (SSO)*.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] A user utilizes a *user agent* (usually a web browser) to request a web resource protected by a SAML *service provider*.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] The service provider, wishing to know the identity of the requesting user, issues an authentication request to a SAML *identity provider* through the user agent.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] The resulting protocol flow is depicted in the following diagram.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] The service provider performs a security check on behalf of the target resource.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] If a valid security context at the service provider already exists, skip steps 2–7.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] The user agent issues a GET request to the SSO service at the URL from step 2.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] URL query parameter) and performs a security check.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] If the user does not have a valid security context, the identity provider identifies the user (details omitted).
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] The user agent issues a POST request to the assertion consumer service at the service provider.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] parameter is taken from the XHTML form at step 4.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] The assertion consumer service processes the response, creates a security context at the service provider and redirects the user agent to the target resource.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Since a security context exists, the service provider returns the resource to the user agent.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] In SAML 1.1, the flow begins with a request to the identity provider's inter-site transfer service at step 3.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] In the example flow above, all depicted exchanges are *front-channel exchanges*, that is, an HTTP user agent (browser) communicates with a SAML entity at each step.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] In particular, there are no *back-channel exchanges* or direct communications between the service provider and the identity provider.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Front-channel exchanges lead to simple protocol flows where all messages are passed *by value* using a simple HTTP binding (GET or POST).
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Indeed, the flow outlined in the previous section is sometimes called the *Lightweight Web Browser SSO Profile*.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Alternatively, for increased security or privacy, messages may be passed *by reference*.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] For example, an identity provider may supply a reference to a SAML assertion (called an *artifact*) instead of transmitting the assertion directly through the user agent.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Subsequently, the service provider requests the actual assertion via a back channel.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Such a back-channel exchange is specified as a SOAP message exchange (SAML over SOAP over HTTP).
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] In general, any SAML exchange over a secure back channel is conducted as a SOAP message exchange.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] On the back channel, SAML specifies the use of SOAP 1.1.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] The use of SOAP as a binding mechanism is optional, however.
[src:saml-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Any given SAML deployment will choose whatever bindings are appropriate.
[src:saml-federation/single-sign-on] True single sign-on allows the user to log in once and access services without re-entering authentication factors.
[src:saml-federation/single-sign-on] It should not be confused with same-sign on (Directory Server Authentication), often accomplished by using the Lightweight Directory Access Protocol (LDAP) and stored LDAP databases on (directory) servers.
[src:saml-federation/single-sign-on] A simple version of single sign-on can be achieved over IP networks using cookies but only if the sites share a common DNS parent domain.
[src:saml-federation/single-sign-on] Conversely, **single sign-off** or **single log-out** (**SLO**) is the property whereby a single action of signing out terminates access to multiple software systems.
[src:saml-federation/single-sign-on] As different applications and resources support different authentication mechanisms, single sign-on must internally store the credentials used for initial authentication and translate them to the credentials required for the different mechanisms.
[src:saml-federation/single-sign-on] Other shared authentication schemes, such as OpenID and OpenID Connect, offer other services that may require users to make choices during a sign-on to a resource, but can be configured for single sign-on if those other services (such as user consent) are disabled.
[src:saml-federation/single-sign-on] An increasing number of federated social logons, like Facebook Connect, do require the user to enter consent choices upon first registration with a new resource, and so are not always single sign-on in the strictest sense.
[src:saml-federation/single-sign-on] SSO shares centralized authentication servers that all other applications and systems use for authentication purposes and combines this with techniques to ensure that users do not have to actively enter their credentials more than once.
[src:saml-federation/single-sign-on] The term *reduced sign-on* (RSO) has been used by some to reflect the fact that *single sign-on* is impractical in addressing the need for different levels of secure access in the enterprise, and as such more than one authentication server may be necessary.
[src:saml-federation/single-sign-on] As single sign-on provides access to many resources once the user is initially authenticated ("keys to the castle"), it increases the negative impact in case the credentials are available to other people and misused.
[src:saml-federation/single-sign-on] Therefore, single sign-on requires an increased focus on the protection of the user credentials, and should ideally be combined with strong authentication methods like smart cards and one-time password tokens.
[src:saml-federation/single-sign-on] Single sign-on also increases dependence on highly-available authentication systems; a loss of their availability can result in denial of access to all systems unified under the SSO.
[src:saml-federation/single-sign-on] SSO can be configured with session failover capabilities in order to maintain the system operation.
[src:saml-federation/single-sign-on] Nonetheless, the risk of system failure may make single sign-on undesirable for systems to which access must be guaranteed at all times, such as security or plant-floor systems.
[src:saml-federation/single-sign-on] Furthermore, the use of single-sign-on techniques utilizing social networking services such as Facebook may render third party websites unusable within libraries, schools, or workplaces that block social media sites for productivity reasons.
[src:saml-federation/single-sign-on] It can also cause difficulties in countries with active censorship regimes, such as China and its "Golden Shield Project", where the third party website may not be actively censored, but is effectively blocked if a user's social login is blocked.
[src:saml-federation/single-sign-on] In March 2012, a research paper reported an extensive study on the security of social login mechanisms.
[src:saml-federation/single-sign-on] The authors found 8 serious logic flaws in high-profile ID providers and relying party websites, such as OpenID (including Google ID and PayPal Access), Facebook, Janrain, Freelancer, FarmVille, and Sears.com.
[src:saml-federation/single-sign-on] Because the researchers informed ID providers and relying party websites prior to public announcement of the discovery of the flaws, the vulnerabilities were corrected, and no security breaches have been reported.
[src:saml-federation/single-sign-on] In May 2014, a vulnerability named Covert Redirect was disclosed.
[src:saml-federation/single-sign-on] It was first reported "Covert Redirect Vulnerability Related to OAuth 2.0 and OpenID" by its discoverer Wang Jing, a Mathematical PhD student from Nanyang Technological University, Singapore.
[src:saml-federation/single-sign-on] In fact, almost all Single sign-on protocols are affected.
[src:saml-federation/single-sign-on] Covert Redirect takes advantage of third-party clients susceptible to cross-site scripting (XSS) or open redirect.
[src:saml-federation/single-sign-on] In December 2020, flaws in federated authentication systems were discovered to have been utilized by attackers during the 2020 United States federal government data breach.
[src:saml-federation/single-sign-on] Another security issue is that if the session used for SSO is stolen (which can be protected with the HttpOnly cookie flag unlike the SSO token), the attacker can access all the websites that are using the SSO system.
[src:saml-federation/single-sign-on] As originally implemented in Kerberos and SAML, single sign-on did not give users any choices about releasing their personal information to each new resource that the user visited.
[src:saml-federation/single-sign-on] This worked well enough within a single enterprise, like MIT where Kerberos was invented, or major corporations where all of the resources were internal sites.
[src:saml-federation/single-sign-on] However, as federated services like Active Directory Federation Services proliferated, the user's private information was sent out to affiliated sites not under control of the enterprise that collected the data from the user.
[src:saml-federation/single-sign-on] Since privacy regulations are now tightening with legislation like the GDPR, the newer methods like OpenID Connect have started to become more attractive; for example MIT, the originator of Kerberos, now supports OpenID Connect.
[src:saml-federation/single-sign-on] Single sign-on in theory can work without revealing identifying information such as email addresses to the relying party (credential consumer), but many credential providers do not allow users to configure what information is passed on to the credential consumer.
[src:saml-federation/single-sign-on] As of 2019, Google and Facebook sign-in do not require users to share email addresses with the credential consumer.
[src:saml-federation/single-sign-on] "Sign in with Apple" introduced in iOS 13 allows a user to request a unique relay email address each time the user signs up for a new service, thus reducing the likelihood of account linking by the credential consumer.
[src:saml-federation/single-sign-on] Windows environment - Windows login fetches TGT.
[src:saml-federation/single-sign-on] Active Directory-aware applications fetch service tickets, so the user is not prompted to re-authenticate.
[src:saml-federation/single-sign-on] Unix/Linux environment - Login via Kerberos PAM modules fetches TGT.
[src:saml-federation/single-sign-on] Kerberized client applications such as Evolution, Firefox, and SVN use service tickets, so the user is not prompted to re-authenticate.
[src:saml-federation/single-sign-on] Mobile environment - Apple added native Kerberos support in IOS 13.
[src:saml-federation/single-sign-on] On Android a Mobile Device Management service can add support for Kerberos.
[src:saml-federation/single-sign-on] Initial sign-on prompts the user for the smart card.
[src:saml-federation/single-sign-on] Additional software applications also use the smart card, without prompting the user to re-enter credentials.
[src:saml-federation/single-sign-on] Smart-card-based single sign-on can either use certificates or passwords stored on the smart card.
[src:saml-federation/single-sign-on] Security Assertion Markup Language (SAML) is an XML-based method for exchanging user security information between an SAML identity provider and a SAML service provider.
[src:saml-federation/single-sign-on] SAML 2.0 supports W3C XML encryption and service-provider–initiated web browser single sign-on exchanges.
[src:saml-federation/single-sign-on] A user wielding a user agent (usually a web browser) is called the subject in SAML-based single sign-on.
[src:saml-federation/single-sign-on] The user requests a web resource protected by a SAML service provider.
[src:saml-federation/single-sign-on] The service provider, wishing to know the identity of the user, issues an authentication request to a SAML identity provider through the user agent.
[src:saml-federation/single-sign-on] The identity provider is the one that provides the user credentials.
[src:saml-federation/single-sign-on] The service provider trusts the user information from the identity provider to provide access to its services or resources.
[src:saml-federation/single-sign-on] A newer variation of single-sign-on authentication has been developed using mobile devices as access credentials.
[src:saml-federation/single-sign-on] A mobile device is "something you have", as opposed to a password which is "something you know", or biometrics (fingerprint, retinal scan, facial recognition, etc.) which is "something you are".
[src:saml-federation/single-sign-on] Security experts recommend using at least two out of these three factors (multi-factor authentication) for best protection.
[src:saml-federation/xml] The design goals of XML emphasize simplicity, generality, and usability across the Internet.
[src:saml-federation/xml] It is a textual data format with strong support via Unicode for different human languages.
[src:saml-federation/xml] Although the design of XML focuses on documents, the language is widely used for the representation of arbitrary data structures, such as those used in web services.
[src:saml-federation/xml] Several schema systems exist to aid in the definition of XML-based languages, while programmers have developed many application programming interfaces (APIs) to aid the processing of XML data.
[src:saml-federation/xml] The main purpose of XML is serialization, i.e. storing, transmitting, and reconstructing arbitrary data.
[src:saml-federation/xml] For two disparate systems to exchange information, they need to agree upon a file format.
[src:saml-federation/xml] It is therefore analogous to a lingua franca for representing information.
[src:saml-federation/xml] As a markup language, XML labels, categorizes, and structurally organizes information.
[src:saml-federation/xml] XML tags represent the data structure and contain metadata.
[src:saml-federation/xml] What is within the tags is data, encoded in the way the XML standard specifies.
[src:saml-federation/xml] An additional XML schema (XSD) defines the necessary metadata for interpreting and validating XML.
[src:saml-federation/xml] (This is also referred to as the canonical schema.) An XML document that adheres to basic XML rules is "well-formed"; one that adheres to its schema is "valid".
[src:saml-federation/xml] IETF RFC 7303 (which supersedes the older RFC 3023), provides rules for the construction of media types for use in XML message.
[src:saml-federation/xml] It defines three media types: `application/xml` (`text/xml` is an alias), `application/xml-external-parsed-entity` (`text/xml-external-parsed-entity` is an alias) and `application/xml-dtd`.
[src:saml-federation/xml] They are used for transmitting raw XML files without exposing their internal semantics.
[src:saml-federation/xml] RFC 7303 further recommends that XML-based languages be given media types ending in `+xml`, for example, `image/svg+xml` for SVG.
[src:saml-federation/xml] Further guidelines for the use of XML in a networked context appear in RFC 3470, also known as IETF BCP 70, a document covering many aspects of designing and deploying an XML-based language.
[src:saml-federation/xml] XML has come into common use for the interchange of data over the Internet.
[src:saml-federation/xml] Hundreds of document formats using XML syntax have been developed, including RSS, Atom, Office Open XML, OpenDocument, SVG, COLLADA, and XHTML.
[src:saml-federation/xml] XML also provides the base language for communication protocols such as SOAP and XMPP.
[src:saml-federation/xml] It is one of the message exchange formats used in the Asynchronous JavaScript and XML (AJAX) programming technique.
[src:saml-federation/xml] Many industry data standards, such as Health Level 7, OpenTravel Alliance, FpML, MISMO, and the National Information Exchange Model are based on XML and the rich features of the XML schema specification.
[src:saml-federation/xml] In publishing, Darwin Information Typing Architecture is an XML industry data standard.
[src:saml-federation/xml] XML is used extensively to underpin various publishing formats.
[src:saml-federation/xml] One of the applications of XML in science is the representation of operational meteorology information based on IWXXM standards.
[src:saml-federation/xml] The material in this section is based on the XML Specification.
[src:saml-federation/xml] This is not an exhaustive list of all the constructs that appear in XML; it provides an introduction to the key constructs most often encountered in day-to-day use.
[src:saml-federation/xml] character (except Null) may appear in an (1.1) XML document (while some are discouraged).
[src:saml-federation/xml] The specification places requirements on what an XML processor must do and not do, but the application is outside its scope.
[src:saml-federation/xml] Strings of characters that are not markup are content.
[src:saml-federation/xml] are classified as markup, while the text between them is classified as content.
[src:saml-federation/xml] In addition, whitespace before and after the outermost element is classified as markup.
[src:saml-federation/xml] is a logical document component that either begins with a start-tag and ends with a matching end-tag or consists only of an empty-element tag.
[src:saml-federation/xml] that exists within a start-tag or empty-element tag.
[src:saml-federation/xml] , where the names of the attributes are "src" and "alt", and their values are "madonna.jpg" and "Madonna" respectively.
[src:saml-federation/xml] , where the name of the attribute is "number" and its value is "3".
[src:saml-federation/xml] An XML attribute can only have a single value and each attribute can appear at most once on each element.
[src:saml-federation/xml] with some format beyond what XML defines itself.
[src:saml-federation/xml] that describes some information about themselves.
[src:saml-federation/xml] XML documents consist entirely of characters from the Unicode repertoire.
[src:saml-federation/xml] Except for a small number of specifically excluded control characters, any character defined by Unicode may appear within the content of an XML document.
[src:saml-federation/xml] XML includes facilities for identifying the *encoding* of the Unicode characters that make up the document, and for expressing characters that, for one reason or another, cannot be used directly.
[src:saml-federation/xml] XML 1.1 extends the set of allowed characters to include all the above, plus the remaining characters in the range U+0001–U+001F.
[src:saml-federation/xml] At the same time, however, it restricts the use of C0 and C1 control characters other than U+0009 (Horizontal Tab), U+000A (Line Feed), U+000D (Carriage Return), and U+0085 (Next Line) by requiring them to be written in escaped form (for example U+0001 must be written as `&#x01;` or its equivalent).
[src:saml-federation/xml] In the case of C1 characters, this restriction is a backwards incompatibility; it was introduced to allow common encoding errors to be detected.
[src:saml-federation/xml] The code point U+0000 (Null) is the only character that is not permitted in any XML 1.1 document.
[src:saml-federation/xml] The Unicode character set can be encoded into bytes for storage or transmission in a variety of different ways, called "encodings".
[src:saml-federation/xml] Unicode itself defines encodings that cover the entire repertoire; well-known ones include UTF-8 (which the XML standard recommends using, without a BOM) and UTF-16.
[src:saml-federation/xml] There are many other text encodings that predate Unicode, such as ASCII and various ISO/IEC 8859; their character repertoires are in every case subsets of the Unicode character set.
[src:saml-federation/xml] XML allows the use of any of the Unicode-defined encodings and any other encodings whose characters also appear in Unicode.
[src:saml-federation/xml] XML also provides a mechanism whereby an XML processor can reliably, without any prior knowledge, determine which encoding is being used.
[src:saml-federation/xml] Encodings other than UTF-8 and UTF-16 are not necessarily recognized by every XML parser (and in some cases not even UTF-16, even though the standard mandates it to also be recognized).
[src:saml-federation/xml] XML provides *escape* facilities for including characters that are problematic to include directly.
[src:saml-federation/xml] All permitted Unicode characters may be represented with a *numeric character reference*.
[src:saml-federation/xml] Consider the Chinese character "中", whose numeric code in Unicode is hexadecimal 4E2D, or decimal 20,013.
[src:saml-federation/xml] A user whose keyboard offers no method for entering this character could still insert it in an XML document encoded either as `&#20013;` or `&#x4e2d;`.
[src:saml-federation/xml] Similarly, the string "I <3 Jörg" could be encoded for inclusion in an XML document as `I &lt;3 J&#xF6;rg`.
[src:saml-federation/xml] `&#0;` is not permitted because the null character is one of the control characters excluded from XML, even when using a numeric character reference.
[src:saml-federation/xml] An alternative encoding mechanism such as Base64 is needed to represent such characters.
[src:saml-federation/xml] Comments may appear anywhere in a document outside other markup.
[src:saml-federation/xml] Comments cannot appear before the XML declaration.
[src:saml-federation/xml] Comments begin with `<!--` and end with `-->`.
[src:saml-federation/xml] For compatibility with SGML, the string "--" (double-hyphen) is not allowed inside comments; this means comments cannot be nested.
[src:saml-federation/xml] The ampersand has no special significance within comments, so entity and character references are not recognized as such, and there is no way to represent characters outside the character set of the document encoding.
[src:saml-federation/xml] XML 1.0 (Fifth Edition) and XML 1.1 support the direct use of almost any Unicode character in element names, attributes, comments, character data, and processing instructions (other than the ones that have special symbolic meaning in XML itself, such as the less-than sign, "<").
[src:saml-federation/xml] The XML specification defines an XML document as a well-formed text, meaning that it satisfies a list of syntax rules provided in the specification.
[src:saml-federation/xml] The definition of an XML document excludes texts that contain violations of well-formedness rules; they are simply not XML.
[src:saml-federation/xml] An XML processor that encounters such a violation is required to report such errors and to cease normal processing.
[src:saml-federation/xml] This policy, occasionally referred to as "draconian error handling", stands in notable contrast to the behavior of programs that process HTML, which are designed to produce a reasonable result even in the presence of severe markup errors.
[src:saml-federation/xml] XML's policy in this area has been criticized as a violation of Postel's law ("Be conservative in what you send; be liberal in what you accept").
[src:saml-federation/xml] The XML specification defines a valid XML document as a well-formed XML document which also conforms to the rules of a Document Type Definition (DTD).
[src:saml-federation/xml] In addition to being well formed, an XML document may be *valid*.
[src:saml-federation/xml] This means that it contains a reference to a Document Type Definition (DTD), and that its elements and attributes are declared in that DTD and follow the grammatical rules for them that the DTD specifies.
[src:saml-federation/xml] XML processors are classified as *validating* or *non-validating* depending on whether or not they check XML documents for validity.
[src:saml-federation/xml] A processor that discovers a validity error must be able to report it, but may continue normal processing.
[src:saml-federation/xml] A DTD is an example of a *schema* or *grammar*.
[src:saml-federation/xml] Since the initial publication of XML 1.0, there has been substantial work in the area of schema languages for XML.
[src:saml-federation/xml] Such schema languages typically constrain the set of elements that may be used in a document, which attributes may be applied to them, the order in which they may appear, and the allowable parent/child relationships.
[src:saml-federation/xml] The oldest schema language for XML is the document type definition (DTD), inherited from SGML.
[src:saml-federation/xml] DTD technology is still used in many applications because of its ubiquity.
[src:saml-federation/xml] A newer schema language, described by the W3C as the successor of DTDs, is XML Schema, often referred to by the initialism for XML Schema instances, XSD (XML Schema Definition).
[src:saml-federation/xml] XSDs are far more powerful than DTDs in describing XML languages.
[src:saml-federation/xml] They use a rich datatyping system and allow for more detailed constraints on an XML document's logical structure.
[src:saml-federation/xml] XSDs also use an XML-based format, which makes it possible to use ordinary XML tools to help process them.
[src:saml-federation/xml] RELAX NG (Regular Language for XML Next Generation) was initially specified by OASIS and is now a standard (Part 2: *Regular-grammar-based validation* of ISO/IEC 19757 – DSDL).
[src:saml-federation/xml] RELAX NG schemas may be written in either an XML based syntax or a more compact non-XML syntax; the two syntaxes are isomorphic and James Clark's conversion tool—Trang—can convert between them without loss of information.
[src:saml-federation/xml] RELAX NG has a simpler definition and validation framework than XML Schema, making it easier to use and implement.
[src:saml-federation/xml] It also has the ability to use datatype framework plug-ins; a RELAX NG schema author, for example, can require values in an XML document to conform to definitions in XML Schema Datatypes.
[src:saml-federation/xml] Schematron is a language for making assertions about the presence or absence of patterns in an XML document.
[src:saml-federation/xml] Schematron is now a standard (Part 3: *Rule-based validation* of ISO/IEC 19757 – DSDL).
[src:saml-federation/xml] DSDL (Document Schema Definition Languages) is a multi-part ISO/IEC standard (ISO/IEC 19757) that brings together a comprehensive set of small schema languages, each targeted at specific problems.
[src:saml-federation/xml] DSDL includes RELAX NG full and compact syntax, Schematron assertion language, and languages for defining datatypes, character repertoire constraints, renaming and entity expansion, and namespace-based routing of document fragments to different validators.
[src:saml-federation/xml] DSDL schema languages do not have the vendor support of XML Schemas yet, and are to some extent a grassroots reaction of industrial publishers to the lack of utility of XML Schemas for publishing.
[src:saml-federation/xml] Some schema languages not only describe the structure of a particular XML format but also offer limited facilities to influence processing of individual XML files that conform to this format.
[src:saml-federation/xml] DTDs and XSDs both have this ability; they can for instance provide the infoset augmentation facility and attribute defaults.
[src:saml-federation/xml] RELAX NG and Schematron intentionally do not provide these.
[src:saml-federation/xml] A cluster of specifications closely related to XML have been developed, starting soon after the initial publication of XML 1.0.
[src:saml-federation/xml] It is frequently the case that the term "XML" is used to refer to XML together with one or more of these other technologies that have come to be seen as part of the XML core.
[src:saml-federation/xml] Some other specifications conceived as part of the "XML Core" have failed to find wide adoption, including XInclude, XLink, and XPointer.
[src:saml-federation/xml] The design goals of XML include, "It shall be easy to write programs which process XML documents." Despite this, the XML specification contains almost no information about how programmers might go about doing such processing.
[src:saml-federation/xml] The XML Infoset specification provides a vocabulary to refer to the constructs within an XML document, but does not provide any guidance on how to access this information.
[src:saml-federation/xml] A variety of APIs for accessing XML have been developed and used, and some have been standardized.
[src:saml-federation/xml] Stream-oriented facilities require less memory and, for certain tasks based on a linear traversal of an XML document, are faster and simpler than other alternatives.
[src:saml-federation/xml] Tree-traversal and data-binding APIs typically require the use of much more memory, but are often found more convenient for use by programmers; some include declarative retrieval of document components via the use of XPath expressions.
[src:saml-federation/xml] XSLT is designed for declarative description of XML document transformations, and has been widely implemented both in server-side packages and Web browsers.
[src:saml-federation/xml] XQuery overlaps XSLT in its functionality, but is designed more for searching of large XML databases.
[src:saml-federation/xml] Simple API for XML (SAX) is a lexical, event-driven API in which a document is read serially and its contents are reported as callbacks to various methods on a handler object of the user's design.
[src:saml-federation/xml] SAX is fast and efficient to implement, but difficult to use for extracting information at random from the XML, since it tends to burden the application author with keeping track of what part of the document is being processed.
[src:saml-federation/xml] It is better suited to situations in which certain types of information are always handled the same way, no matter where they occur in the document.
[src:saml-federation/xml] Pull parsing treats the document as a series of items read in sequence using the iterator design pattern.
[src:saml-federation/xml] A pull parser creates an iterator that sequentially visits the various elements, attributes, and data in an XML document.
[src:saml-federation/xml] Code that uses this iterator can test the current item (to tell, for example, whether it is a start-tag or end-tag, or text), and inspect its attributes (local name, namespace, values of XML attributes, value of text, etc.), and can also move the iterator to the next item.
[src:saml-federation/xml] The code can thus extract information from the document as it traverses it.
[src:saml-federation/xml] The recursive-descent approach tends to lend itself to keeping data as typed local variables in the code doing the parsing, while SAX, for instance, typically requires a parser to manually maintain intermediate data within a stack of elements that are parent elements of the element being parsed.
[src:saml-federation/xml] Pull-parsing code can be more straightforward to understand and maintain than SAX parsing code.
[src:saml-federation/xml] The Document Object Model (DOM) is an interface that allows for navigation of the entire document as if it were a tree of node objects representing the document's contents.
[src:saml-federation/xml] A DOM document can be created by a parser, or can be generated manually by users (with limitations).
[src:saml-federation/xml] Data types in DOM nodes are abstract; implementations provide their own programming language-specific bindings.
[src:saml-federation/xml] DOM implementations tend to be memory intensive, as they generally require the entire document to be loaded into memory and constructed as a tree of objects before access is allowed.
[src:saml-federation/xml] XML data binding is a technique for simplifying development of applications that need to work with XML documents.
[src:saml-federation/xml] It involves mapping the XML document to a hierarchy of strongly typed objects, rather than using the generic objects created by a DOM parser.
[src:saml-federation/xml] The resulting code is often easier to read and maintain, and it can help to identify problems at compile time rather than run-time.
[src:saml-federation/xml] XML data binding is particularly well-suited for applications where the document structure is known and fixed at the time the application is written.
[src:saml-federation/xml] By creating a strongly typed representation of the XML data, developers can take advantage of modern integrated development environments (IDEs) that provide features like auto-complete, code refactoring, and code highlighting.
[src:saml-federation/xml] This can make it easier to write correct and efficient code, and reduce the risk of errors and bugs.
[src:saml-federation/xml] Example data-binding systems include the Java Architecture for XML Binding (JAXB), XML Serialization in .NET Framework, and XML serialization in gSOAP.
[src:saml-federation/xml] XML has appeared as a first-class data type in other languages.
[src:saml-federation/xml] The ECMAScript for XML (E4X) extension to the ECMAScript/JavaScript language explicitly defines two specific objects (XML and XMLList) for JavaScript, which support XML document nodes and XML node lists as distinct objects and use a dot-notation specifying parent-child relationships.
[src:saml-federation/xml] E4X is supported by the Mozilla 2.5+ browsers (though now deprecated) and Adobe Actionscript but has not been widely adopted.
[src:saml-federation/xml] Similar notations are used in Microsoft's LINQ implementation for Microsoft .NET 3.5 and above, and in Scala (which uses the Java VM).
[src:saml-federation/xml] The open-source xmlsh application, which provides a Linux-like shell with special features for XML manipulation, similarly treats XML as a data type, using the <[ ]> notation.
[src:saml-federation/xml] The Resource Description Framework defines a data type `rdf:XMLLiteral` to hold wrapped, canonical XML.
[src:saml-federation/xml] Facebook has produced extensions to the PHP and JavaScript languages that add XML to the core syntax in a similar fashion to E4X, namely XHP and JSX respectively.
[src:saml-federation/xml] XML is an application profile of SGML (ISO 8879).
[src:saml-federation/xml] The versatility of SGML for dynamic information display was understood by early digital media publishers in the late 1980s prior to the rise of the Internet.
[src:saml-federation/xml] By the mid-1990s some practitioners of SGML had gained experience with the then-new World Wide Web, and believed that SGML offered solutions to some of the problems the Web was likely to face as it grew.
[src:saml-federation/xml] Dan Connolly added SGML to the list of W3C's activities when he joined the staff in 1995; work began in mid-1996 when Sun Microsystems engineer Jon Bosak developed a charter and recruited collaborators.
[src:saml-federation/xml] Bosak was well-connected in the small community of people who had experience both in SGML and the Web.
[src:saml-federation/xml] XML was compiled by a working group of eleven members, supported by a (roughly) 150-member Interest Group.
[src:saml-federation/xml] Technical debate took place on the Interest Group mailing list and issues were resolved by consensus or, when that failed, majority vote of the Working Group.
[src:saml-federation/xml] A record of design decisions and their rationales was compiled by Michael Sperberg-McQueen on December 4, 1997.
[src:saml-federation/xml] James Clark served as Technical Lead of the Working Group, notably contributing the empty-element `<empty />` syntax and the name "XML".
[src:saml-federation/xml] Other names that had been put forward for consideration included "MAGMA" (Minimal Architecture for Generalized Markup Applications), "SLIM" (Structured Language for Internet Markup) and "MGML" (Minimal Generalized Markup Language).
[src:saml-federation/xml] The co-editors of the specification were originally Tim Bray and Michael Sperberg-McQueen.
[src:saml-federation/xml] Halfway through the project, Bray accepted a consulting engagement with Netscape, provoking vociferous protests from Microsoft.
[src:saml-federation/xml] Bray was temporarily asked to resign the editorship.
[src:saml-federation/xml] This led to intense dispute in the Working Group, eventually solved by the appointment of Microsoft's Jean Paoli as a third co-editor.
[src:saml-federation/xml] The XML Working Group communicated primarily through email and weekly teleconferences.
[src:saml-federation/xml] The major design decisions were reached in a short burst of intense work between August and November 1996, when the first Working Draft of an XML specification was published.
[src:saml-federation/xml] Further design work continued through 1997, and XML 1.0 became a W3C Recommendation on February 10, 1998.
